Time and Date

System Time and System Date

Boot and enter the BIOS setup. Use the F5/F6 keys or numeric keys to change the system time and date fields to several different valid values. Save, exit (or just exit), reboot and confirm the changes take effect after each change.


Note: the time must be stated in 24 hour military time if "AM/PM" is not present.


From x90 projects:


PgUp/Slide up : Increase


PgDn/Slide down : Reduce

The F5/F6 keys and numeric keys can change the time and date.


From x90 projects:PgUp/Slide up and PgDn/Slide down can change the time and date.

Boot to BIOS setup. Attempt to use non-numeric characters for the numeric inputs to change the time and date (i.e. a-Z, !@#$%^&*). Attempt to input invalid times (i.e. 37 as an hour input, 60 for minutes and seconds) to change the system time and date.

The system time and date fields do not accept invalid inputs.

Set the time/date in BIOS setup to the next leap year as shown in the example below:


Example: Time: 23:59:45 Date: 02/28/2012 Observe the time second count change to 00:00:00. Date should transition to 02/29/2012.

Verify that the BIOS date correctly rolls over to 02/29.

Set the time/date in BIOS setup to the next no-leap year as shown in the example below:


Example: Time: 23:59:45 Date: 02/28/2011 Observe the time second count change to 00:00:00. Date should transition to 03/01/2011.

Verify that the BIOS date correctly rolls over to 03/01.

CMOS data and time run normal .

On BIOS Screen and battery in, plug-unplug AC 20 cycle , check CMOS data and time .

CMOS data and time run normal .

Storage Controller working mode

Please hidden the "SATA Controller Mode", if platform support Intel VMD Controller.

Storage policy should follow below scenario (Ship configuration):


For Intel platform (Spec <Lenovo BIOS Optane Support> ) :


HDD/SATA SSD/HDD + SATA SSD : hidden storage controller mode, default is AHCI;


Single PCIE SSD : show storage controller mode, default is AHCI and selectable;


PCIE SSD + HDD/SATA SSD: show storage controller mode, default is RST and selectable;


Optane memory + HDD/SATA SSD: show storage controller mode, default is RST and selectable;


PCIE x 2 (+ HDD/SATA SSD): show storage controller mode, default is RST and selectable;


Intel Teton Glacier SSD: show storage controller mode, default is RST and selectable;


For AMD platform: if the product supports RAID, it will show storage controller mode, default is AHCI.
If project support both PCIe SSD and HDD but may ship with HDD only configuration. Get a HDD only unit, check the storage controller mode in BIOS setup.
Storage controller mode should be hidden in BIOS setup, HDD can be detected.
Plug in a piece of PCIe SSD, check storage controller mode in BIOS setup.
Storage controller mode should show in BIOS setup and AHCI mode is selected.
If project support two SSD port but ship only one ssd storage. Check storage controller mode in BIOS setup.
Storage controller mode should be AHCI mode and selectable.
Plug in another piece of PCIe SSD, check storage controller mode in BIOS setup.
Make sure the new SSD is detected and storage controller mode keep AHCI mode and selectable.

UMA Frame Buffer size


Note: this item only for AMD platform project, please confirm with project whether support or not. If support, please cover all memory size configuration.


Platform and project dependent.


For AMD Platform. Optional for AMD platform and detail settings could be customized by project.


Typically, a larger UMA Frame Buffer Size can lead to faster LLM inference speed.

Default value is 512M for Gaming series


 


Ensure all default size show correctlly.


Note:


1.The default value of 'UMA Frame Buffer Size' depends on the products.


2. From PHX and later AMD platforms, if the UMA frame buffer size set to 512Mb in the BIOS setup, the dedicated video memory size may less than 512MB(may be in a range of 4xx to 512Mb) which is a non-accurate number. That is an expected behavior.
Boot to OS, run command: msinfo32, check Total Physical Memory and record the data.

Go to Settings -> System -> Display -> Advanced display settings -> Display adapter properties for Display 1, check Dedicated Video Memory size.
Go to BIOS setup again, change UMA Frame Buffer Size. Save and exit.

Check Dedicated Video Memory size.

Ensure the size show the same as BIOS setup UMA Frame Buffer Size.



Note: Driver tell the size to OS ,and For RMB,confirm with AMD driver owner the remaining of FB should be between 481~512., OS get the amount and round up by 32 MByte. So the amount of video memory that is showing at OS side is not an accurate number, so It is by MS's alotithm,it is expected behavior.

Check Total Physical Memory size, and compare the data with before changed.

For system installed memory is >6G & < 24G,


when changed UMA Frame Buffer Size from 2G to 1G, Total Physical Memory size should increase 1G;


when changed UMA Frame Buffer Size from 2G to 512M, Total Physical Memory size should increase 1.5G.


For system installed memory is >= 24G,


when changed UMA Frame Buffer Size from 4G to 2G, Total Physical Memory size should increase 2G;


when changed UMA Frame Buffer Size from 4G to 1G, Total Physical Memory size should increase 3G.


when changed UMA Frame Buffer Size from 4G to 512MB, Total Physical Memory size should increase 3.5G.

If system Graphic Device option is Switchable/Dynamic Graphics and Integrated Graphics, please change graphic device to UMA Grphics to check UMA Frame Buffer size function.

Ensure UMA Frame Buffer size works normally.

Allow Microsoft 3rd Party UEFI CA [Enabled/Disabled] // default: Disabled

This item only valid on projects support MSFT Security Level 3.

1. Boot to OS, run Administrator PowerShell and input below command


[System.Text.Encoding]::UTF8.GetString((Get-SecureBootUEFI db).bytes) -match 'Microsoft Corporation UEFI CA 2011'

Ensure return False
2. Reboot system to BIOS setup menu, Enable "Allow Microsoft 3rd Party UEFI CA" and save and exit.

3.Boot to OS, run administrator powershell,


Command:[System.Text.Encoding]::UTF8.GetString((Get-SecureBootUEFI db).bytes) -match 'Microsoft Corporation UEFI CA 2011'

Ensure return: True
4. Reboot system to BIOS setup menu.
5. Execut "Restore Factory Keys"
"Allow Microsoft 3rd Party UEFI CA" this option will be disabled.
Change language setting to "ä¸­æ–‡", repeat above steps.
Ensure all options' information and function is OK.

Microsoft UEFI CA 2023 Check

Check Windows UEFI CA 2023 DB for the project cut in the PCR for sustaining afftected, Gen 11 and later projects


Consumer NB CP20250617_0005 Add Microsoft UEFI CA 2023 and Microsoft Option ROM UEFI CA 2023


SMB NB CP20250421_0006 Add Microsoft UEFI CA 2023 and Microsoft Option ROM UEFI CA 2023




Run in administrator privileges power shell:


[System.Text.Encoding]::ASCII.GetString((Get-SecureBootUEFI db).bytes) -match 'Windows UEFI CA 2023'

Ensure return: True
